"Forman S., Hungerford N., Yamakawa M., Yanase T., Tsai H.-J., Joo Y.-S., Yang D.-K., Nha J.-J.","Climate change impacts and risks for animal health in Asia",2008,"OIE Revue Scientifique et Technique","27","2",,"581","597",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53349176774&partnerID=40&md5=6970e9f6a02e99bc0c6a8a95bb620b77","World Bank, 1818 H Street NW, Washington, DC 20433, United States; World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE), Southeast Asia Foot and Mouth Disease Campaign, C/O Department of Livestock Development, 69/1 Phaya Thai Road, Ratchathewi 10400, Bangkok, Thailand; Kyushu Research Station, National Institute of Animal Health, Chuzan, Kagoshima Kagoshima, 891-0105, Japan; Department of Veterinary Medicine, National Taiwan University, 1 Roosevelt Road, Taipei 106, Taiwan; National Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service, 480 Anyang 6-dong Anyang, Gyeonggi-do 430-824, South Korea","Forman, S., World Bank, 1818 H Street NW, Washington, DC 20433, United States; Hungerford, N., World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE), Southeast Asia Foot and Mouth Disease Campaign, C/O Department of Livestock Development, 69/1 Phaya Thai Road, Ratchathewi 10400, Bangkok, Thailand; Yamakawa, M., Kyushu Research Station, National Institute of Animal Health, Chuzan, Kagoshima Kagoshima, 891-0105, Japan; Yanase, T., Kyushu Research Station, National Institute of Animal Health, Chuzan, Kagoshima Kagoshima, 891-0105, Japan; Tsai, H.-J., Department of Veterinary Medicine, National Taiwan University, 1 Roosevelt Road, Taipei 106, Taiwan; Joo, Y.-S., National Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service, 480 Anyang 6-dong Anyang, Gyeonggi-do 430-824, South Korea; Yang, D.-K., National Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service, 480 Anyang 6-dong Anyang, Gyeonggi-do 430-824, South Korea; Nha, J.-J., National Veterinary Research and Quarantine Service, 480 Anyang 6-dong Anyang, Gyeonggi-do 430-824, South Korea","The threat of climate change and global warming is now recognised worldwide and some alarming manifestations of change have occurred. The Asian continent, because of its size and diversity, may be affected significantly by the consequences of climate change, and its new status as a 'hub' of livestock production gives it an important role in mitigating possible impacts of climate variability on animal health. Animal health may be affected by climate change in four ways: heat-related diseases and stress, extreme weather events, adaptation of animal production systems to new environments, and emergence or re-emergence of infectious diseases, especially vector-borne diseases critically dependent on environmental and climatic conditions. To face these new menaces, the need for strong and efficient Veterinary Services is irrefutable, combined with good coordination of public health services, as many emerging human diseases are zoonoses. Asian developing countries have acute weaknesses in their Veterinary Services, which jeopardises the global surveillance network essential for early detection of hazards. Indeed, international cooperation within and outside Asia is vital to mitigating the risks of climate change to animal health in Asia.","Animal disease; Animal health; Asia; Climate change; Impact; Surveillance; Vector-borne disease; Veterinary Services","animal; animal disease; animal welfare; article; Asia; climate; communicable disease; disease carrier; environment; greenhouse effect; health survey; human; infection control; international cooperation; methodology; public health; risk assessment; stress; zoonosis; Animal Diseases; Animal Welfare; Animals; Asia; Climate; Communicable Disease Control; Communicable Diseases, Emerging; Disease Reservoirs; Disease Vectors; Environment; Greenhouse Effect; Humans; International Cooperation; Public Health; Risk Assessment; Sentinel Surveillance; Stress; Zoonoses; Animalia",,,,,,"(2007) Climate change and agriculture, , http://www.aciar.gov.au/node/2391, Australian Centre for Inter